45:47.000 --> 45:49.000
is a thing that even Darwin had already recognised,

45:49.000 --> 45:51.000
that in some sense,

45:51.000 --> 45:54.000
when you have very modern forms that are very sophisticated,

45:54.000 --> 45:57.000
it's difficult for the things that gave rise to those modern forms

45:57.000 --> 45:59.000
to be recreated.

45:59.000 --> 46:00.000
So for instance,

46:00.000 --> 46:03.000
I'm trying to think of something in the technological realm,

46:03.000 --> 46:05.000
if there's some tremendous amount of effort

46:05.000 --> 46:07.000
that's required to make the first digital computer,

46:07.000 --> 46:10.000
and it's as big as this room and uses as much electricity as a city,

46:10.000 --> 46:13.000
and then you have that thing sitting over there on the desk.

46:13.000 --> 46:15.000
People would not be willing to go through the same effort

46:15.000 --> 46:17.000
to do the same difficult thing again,

46:17.000 --> 46:20.000
once the efficient things are already there.

46:20.000 --> 46:23.000
So I should be careful.

46:23.000 --> 46:26.000
What you said the first time seems to be exactly right,

46:26.000 --> 46:28.000
that we have never found any place where the process

46:28.000 --> 46:30.000
of the emergence of life is being repeated,

46:30.000 --> 46:32.000
but the second thing,

46:32.000 --> 46:34.000
we've never found any place in the earth

46:34.000 --> 46:36.000
that doesn't have something living there.

46:36.000 --> 46:39.000
So you drill down as deep as you can in an oil well,

46:39.000 --> 46:42.000
and you'll find bacteria and archaea living down there.

46:42.000 --> 46:44.000
You go up into arctic ices, they're there.

46:44.000 --> 46:47.000
Up in the atmosphere, they're up there feeding off dust particles.

46:47.000 --> 46:50.000
So in some sense, anywhere there's energy in the world,

46:50.000 --> 46:52.000
something is already grazing on it.

46:52.000 --> 46:55.000
And I think most people do not expect

46:55.000 --> 47:00.000
any catastrophic surprises in that area.

47:00.000 --> 47:03.000
They think that we don't see the emergence of life again,

47:03.000 --> 47:05.000
because current life is so much more efficient.

47:05.000 --> 47:07.000
But then the question about the lab

47:07.000 --> 47:09.000
really is pertinent to what we do.

47:09.000 --> 47:12.000
And so the interesting thing is that

47:12.000 --> 47:15.000
not only is life complex, but the geological world is complex.

47:15.000 --> 47:18.000
And so here's the best thing we can do in the lab.

47:18.000 --> 47:20.000
There are probably three guys in the United States

47:20.000 --> 47:23.000
who can do it, and I'm privileged to be sort of

47:23.000 --> 47:26.000
on the doorstep of one of them asking for what he knows.

47:26.000 --> 47:29.000
You can take a fantastically expensive machine

47:29.000 --> 47:31.000
that took you most of your career to build.

47:31.000 --> 47:34.000
You can put a little bit of chemistry into a gold capsule.

47:34.000 --> 47:35.000
You can seal it.

47:35.000 --> 47:37.000
You can compress it to 300 atmospheres

47:37.000 --> 47:39.000
and heat it to 200 degrees.

47:39.000 --> 47:42.000
And then you can take it out and very carefully open it

47:42.000 --> 47:43.000
and find out what happened.

47:43.000 --> 47:45.000
And if you don't have the chemistry exactly right,

47:45.000 --> 47:46.000
you can start over.

47:46.000 --> 47:50.000
So compare that to what was happening in the early earth.

47:50.000 --> 47:55.000
In the early earth, the mantle was more fluid,

47:55.000 --> 47:57.000
and so there probably were no lasting continents.

47:57.000 --> 47:59.000
It was constantly fractured.

47:59.000 --> 48:01.000
The moon was as big as a dinner plate in the sky,

48:01.000 --> 48:03.000
and the tides were once every six hours

48:03.000 --> 48:06.000
and probably two kilometers high.

48:06.000 --> 48:08.000
The entire ocean probably got cycled

48:08.000 --> 48:10.000
through these hydrothermal systems

48:10.000 --> 48:12.000
on the order of once every 1,000 years,

48:12.000 --> 48:15.000
whereas today it's more like once every 100,000 years.

48:15.000 --> 48:18.000
And I told you that there were two of these systems today

48:18.000 --> 48:20.000
that are sort of separate and sort of different

48:20.000 --> 48:22.000
with their unrelated chemistry.

48:22.000 --> 48:24.000
One is alkaline, one is acid, one has low metals,

48:24.000 --> 48:26.000
one has high metals.

48:26.000 --> 48:29.000
In the early earth, the entire upper crust

48:29.000 --> 48:31.000
was probably fractured with the ocean

48:31.000 --> 48:32.000
infecting through it.

48:32.000 --> 48:34.000
And the chemistry at that time

48:34.000 --> 48:36.000
could have been any mix of any of these things.

48:36.000 --> 48:40.000
So if we want to understand and recreate correctly

48:40.000 --> 48:42.000
in the lab this organic chemistry,

48:42.000 --> 48:45.000
we have to understand what type of chemical environment

48:45.000 --> 48:46.000
we're looking in.

48:46.000 --> 48:48.000
And that turns out to be a really hard search problem.

48:48.000 --> 48:51.000
Works better if you have the entire crust of the earth

48:51.000 --> 48:53.000
than if you have a little gold capsule

48:53.000 --> 48:57.000
that holds less than this much of my finger of a liquid.

48:57.000 --> 49:01.000
But I am hoping that I will live to see these experiments done.

49:01.000 --> 49:03.000
I should tell you that for the citric acid,

49:03.000 --> 49:05.000
the Krebs cycle that I showed you,

49:05.000 --> 49:08.000
George Cody and Carnegie Institution in Washington

49:08.000 --> 49:10.000
has already gotten big arcs of this cycle to go

49:10.000 --> 49:12.000
even with his little capsule.

49:12.000 --> 49:14.000
And so the question is whether at the places

49:14.000 --> 49:16.000
where things are not working,

49:16.000 --> 49:18.000
we're missing something about the mineral chemistry.

49:18.000 --> 49:20.000
And I think that that's probably the case

49:20.000 --> 49:22.000
and that it will probably be cracked.

49:22.000 --> 49:23.000
OK.

